content.text: This is a HE WSI of a CRC case, consisting of lymph nodes or primary tumor section. What is your initial impression of this image?

The thumbnail displays multiple (approximately 10-12) discrete pieces of tissue, most of which have the characteristic ovoid shape and basophilic (purple) staining of lymph nodes. The tissues are embedded in what appears to be fibroadipose tissue. There is also some blue pigment present in the central part of the slide, likely tattoo ink from a prior endoscopic procedure. The overall impression is a lymph node dissection from a colorectal cancer resection, requiring evaluation for metastatic disease.
Are there any places you want to look into further? Give me reasons why you want to look into each region.

As a pathologist, my task is to systematically examine every lymph node for evidence of metastasis. I am zooming into this specific area because it represents one of the lymph nodes, located in the upper-left portion of the slide. This is the starting point of my systematic review of all the lymph nodes present on the slide to determine the N stage. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, I would systematically examine every lymph node on the slide. The green box highlights one of the smaller, well-circumscribed lymph nodes located in the upper left quadrant (the third distinct node from the top-left). I am zooming into this area to assess its architecture at higher magnification. Specifically, I am examining the subcapsular sinus and the parenchyma to look for any infiltration by atypical epithelial cells, which would indicate metastatic carcinoma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my protocol for a cancer case is to meticulously examine every single lymph node for evidence of metastasis. The green box is placed over one of the larger, centrally located lymph nodes. I would zoom into this specific area as part of a systematic review of all the nodes on the slide. This particular node appears to have some textural variation at low power, which warrants closer inspection at higher magnification to assess its architecture and to search for any atypical cell clusters or glandular formations indicative of metastatic carcinoma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I would zoom into this area as part of a systematic examination of all lymph nodes on the slide. This particular node, located centrally, is one of the larger ones present, making it a high-priority target for evaluation. Its dense and uniform cellularity at low power necessitates a closer look to assess the architecture and cell types. The goal is to carefully screen for any non-lymphoid cell clusters that would indicate metastatic carcinoma, which can sometimes be subtle. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my goal is to systematically evaluate every piece of tissue that could be a lymph node to search for metastasis. The area highlighted by the green box is one of the smaller, distinct tissue nodules located in the lower-central part of the slide. It's essential to examine every node, regardless of its size. I would zoom into this area to confirm it is indeed lymphoid tissue and to meticulously inspect its architecture and cellular components for any atypical cells or features suggestive of metastatic carcinoma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, I would systematically examine every lymph node on the slide to look for evidence of metastasis. The selected area of interest is one of these lymph nodes (approximately the fourth major node from the top, in the right-central part of the slide). This particular node is located adjacent to an area of blue surgical ink, which always requires careful inspection. Furthermore, even at low power, the node appears to have some architectural irregularities and darker pigmentation, which warrants a closer look to rule out metastasis or other pathology. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. When evaluating a case for lymph node metastasis, it is standard practice to systematically examine every single lymph node identified. The pathologist has zoomed into this area at the bottom right because it is one of the lymph nodes that needs to be assessed. There is nothing uniquely suspicious about this particular node from the low-power view; this is simply part of a methodical, comprehensive examination of all submitted lymph nodes to ensure none are missed. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, I would systematically review every lymph node on the slide. The green box is positioned on one of the lymph nodes located in the lower right quadrant. This node appears densely cellular and solid. My reason for zooming in is to perform a high-power examination of this specific lymph node to assess its architecture and cellular components for any evidence of metastatic tumor cells, which is a critical part of staging the cancer. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my goal is to systematically examine every lymph node on the slide to determine if cancer has spread. The area indicated by the green box contains one of the smaller lymph nodes, located at the bottom right of the image (it's the second node from the right on the bottom row). Even if a lymph node appears normal at low magnification, it must be carefully inspected at high power to rule out the presence of micrometastases or isolated tumor cells, which can be subtle. This zoom is part of that routine, systematic screening process. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As part of the staging process for colorectal cancer, every lymph node must be meticulously examined for evidence of metastasis. The selected area is one of these lymph nodes. I am systematically reviewing each node on the slide, and this is one in the sequence (the lymph node in the upper right). At low power, its overall shape and color warrant closer inspection to differentiate between reactive changes, pigment deposition, and potential metastatic tumor deposits. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my protocol is to systematically examine every piece of tissue that represents a lymph node. The area selected for zoom is one of these lymph nodes, located on the right side of the slide. In the low-power view, this node appears partially effaced. There is a dense, dark purple area, likely residual lymphoid tissue, but also a significant portion that is paler and has a more disorganized texture. This irregular interface is a key feature that warrants high-magnification review to determine if the paler area is a normal fatty hilum, a reactive process, or, more likely, an infiltration by metastatic carcinoma. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. I am systematically examining each piece of tissue that resembles a lymph node. The area indicated by the green box is one of these lymph nodes, specifically the most prominent one on the far left side of the slide. I would zoom into this area to assess its architecture and cellular detail at high magnification, looking for any abnormal cell clusters, glandular structures, or other features that would indicate the presence of metastatic adenocarcinoma, which is the key task for a lymph node slide in a colorectal cancer case. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my task is to meticulously examine every lymph node on the slide to screen for metastasis. The green box is placed on the second lymph node from the top-left. I would zoom into this area as part of my systematic review. At low power, this particular node appears somewhat irregular and has a heterogeneous texture with paler areas, which raises suspicion for the replacement of normal lymphoid tissue by a tumor deposit, prompting a high-magnification look. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found]. As a pathologist, my standard procedure for staging colorectal cancer is to meticulously examine every single lymph node identified in the specimen. The area highlighted by the green box contains one of these lymph nodes, located in the lower right quadrant. I would zoom into this area as part of my systematic review of all nodes to assess it at high magnification. The goal is to carefully search for any evidence of metastatic carcinoma, which would appear as clusters of atypical epithelial cells, often forming glands, that are foreign to the normal lymph node architecture. I want to zoom into [coordinates not found].
This is ROI 1 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In the zoomed-in view, I see a section of a lymph node characterized by dense lymphoid tissue with follicular structures. Within the lymphoid parenchyma, there are scattered adipocytes (fat cells) and, more importantly, several small, well-formed glandular structures. These glands are lined by cuboidal to columnar epithelium that appears relatively bland, without significant cytologic atypia or mitotic activity. The presence of glands within a lymph node in the context of colorectal cancer raises suspicion for metastatic adenocarcinoma. However, the bland appearance of these glands is also highly suggestive of benign nodal inclusions (ectopic glands). At this point, this node is suspicious but likely negative for malignancy. I would carefully examine the rest of the node and other nodes for more definitive features of metastasis.
This is ROI 2 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in area, I see the periphery of a lymph node. The upper portion of the image shows dense lymphoid tissue composed of a population of small, dark lymphocytes, consistent with the lymph node cortex. The lower portion shows the lymph node capsule and the surrounding perinodal adipose tissue. I am carefully examining the subcapsular sinus, which is the space just beneath the capsule. In this specific field of view, I do not see any nests or single cells of metastatic adenocarcinoma. The architecture appears preserved. My impression is that this portion of the lymph node is negative for malignancy and appears to be a reactive lymph node.
This is ROI 3 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in image shows a fascinating and somewhat unexpected finding. The lower portion of the image displays a dense, solid aggregate of small, dark lymphocytes, which is consistent with the cortex of a lymph node. However, the upper portion of the image shows the unmistakable architecture of lung parenchyma, with alveolar spaces and septa. The alveolar walls are heavily infiltrated by lymphocytes, and there are black pigment deposits, which is anthracotic pigment (carbon). My impression is that this is an intrapulmonary lymph node or a hilar lymph node directly adjacent to lung tissue. The primary finding here is the juxtaposition of lung tissue and a lymph node, with the lung showing a marked lymphocytic infiltrate. In this particular field, there are no clear signs of metastatic adenocarcinoma. The finding of lung tissue is unusual for a standard colorectal cancer resection, suggesting this might be from a lung metastasis resection or a more extensive dissection.
This is ROI 4 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in area shows the edge of a dense lymphoid aggregate on the right, interfacing with adjacent tissue on the left. The lymphoid aggregate is composed of a monotonous population of small, dark, round cells consistent with lymphocytes. I do not see any atypical glandular structures, nests of large pleomorphic epithelial cells, or significant necrosis to suggest metastatic colorectal adenocarcinoma. The tissue on the left contains alveolar spaces and blood vessels, which is characteristic of lung parenchyma. My impression is that this is likely an intrapulmonary lymph node or a large peribronchial lymphoid aggregate. Based on this view, the lymph node is negative for metastasis.
This is ROI 5 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in view reveals a portion of a lymph node. The most prominent feature is the presence of abundant black, granular pigment within the sinuses, consistent with anthracotic pigment. This pigment is contained within macrophages (histiocytes), leading to sinus expansion (sinus histiocytosis). There are also congested blood vessels. I do not see any definite clusters of atypical epithelial cells to suggest metastasis in this field. My impression is that this is a reactive lymph node with prominent anthracosis and sinus histiocytosis, which are benign findings.
This is ROI 6 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In the zoomed-in area, I see a portion of a lymph node on the left and surrounding fibro-adipose tissue on the right. The lymph node tissue is composed of dense sheets of lymphocytes. There are prominent, coarse, black granular pigment deposits scattered throughout, which are characteristic of anthracotic pigment (carbon) within macrophages. This is a common and benign finding in regional lymph nodes. The tissue on the right shows mature adipose tissue and connective tissue with blue surgical ink on the surface. My impression of this specific area is a benign, reactive lymph node with significant anthracosis. I do not see any evidence of metastatic carcinoma in this field of view.
This is ROI 7 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in view shows a lymph node with a dense population of small, mature-appearing lymphocytes. There are some reactive changes, including prominent sinuses and some small, pale germinal centers. Crucially, I do not see any atypical epithelial cells, abnormal glandular structures, or clusters of malignant cells within the lymphoid parenchyma. The tissue at the top of the image contains some glandular elements and blood vessels, which could be part of the adjacent primary tumor or normal colonic tissue near the node. Based on this high-power view of the lymph node itself, my impression is that it is a reactive lymph node, negative for metastasis.
This is ROI 8 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-power view, I see a lymph node that is partially replaced by a tumor. There is a distinct interface between the residual lymphoid tissue (top and left), composed of small, dark lymphocytes, and a large infiltrate of malignant cells (bottom and right). These malignant cells are arranged in a solid sheet and are characterized by large size, abundant eosinophilic cytoplasm, pleomorphic nuclei, and prominent nucleoli. These features are characteristic of metastatic adenocarcinoma. My impression is that this is a positive lymph node, containing metastatic carcinoma consistent with a colorectal primary.
This is ROI 9 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-magnification view, I see a dense and diffuse population of small, round cells with dark nuclei and scant cytoplasm, which are characteristic of lymphocytes. This is the normal cellular composition of a lymph node. I can also identify several small blood vessels (high endothelial venules) scattered throughout. Critically, there are no atypical epithelial cells, nests of tumor cells, or glandular structures to suggest metastatic carcinoma. There is a dark, smudgy artifact in the upper right quadrant of the view, which is non-diagnostic. My impression of this area is that it is a benign/reactive lymph node, negative for metastasis.
This is ROI 10 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

The zoomed-in view shows a section of a lymph node with preserved lymphoid follicles. There is a significant amount of coarse, black, granular pigment deposited within the sinuses and parenchyma of the node. This pigment is being engulfed by macrophages (histiocytes). This finding is characteristic of carbon pigment or, more likely in this context, India ink used to mark the site of the tumor during a prior colonoscopy ('tattoo'). The lymphoid tissue appears reactive, but I do not see definitive clusters of malignant epithelial cells in this field of view. My impression is a reactive lymph node with extensive iatrogenic pigment deposition. The entire node must be examined to definitively rule out metastasis.
This is ROI 11 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in area, my suspicion is confirmed. On the left side of the image, there is a dense sheet of small, dark lymphocytes, which represents the remaining, compressed normal lymph node tissue. The majority of the field, to the right, shows infiltration by malignant cells. These cells are arranged in irregular, crowded, and fused glandular structures (cribriform architecture), which is characteristic of metastatic adenocarcinoma. The tumor cells have more abundant pink (eosinophilic) cytoplasm compared to the surrounding lymphocytes. My impression is definitive: this is a positive lymph node containing metastatic adenocarcinoma.
This is ROI 12 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this zoomed-in view, I see the architecture of a lymph node. There is a dense population of small, round, dark-staining cells, which are lymphocytes. I can identify lymphoid follicles, which are characteristic of normal or reactive lymphoid tissue. I do not see any definite atypical epithelial cells, abnormal glands, or nests of tumor cells that would suggest metastasis. The overall impression of this specific field of view is a benign or reactive lymph node, with no evidence of malignancy.
This is ROI 13 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In this high-magnification view, I see a portion of a lymph node that is heavily infiltrated by a tumor. The bottom part of the image shows residual, dense lymphoid tissue composed of small, dark lymphocytes. The upper part of the image shows that the normal lymph node structure has been largely replaced by malignant glands, characteristic of metastatic adenocarcinoma. These glands are irregular, with crowded, atypical epithelial cells showing nuclear pleomorphism and hyperchromasia. Crucially, I can see infiltration of these malignant glands into the surrounding perinodal adipose tissue (fat cells) at the top of the image. My impression is that this is a positive lymph node containing metastatic adenocarcinoma with evidence of extranodal extension (ENE).
This is ROI 14 and its 40x cyto pattern. What do you observe when you zoom in?

In the zoomed-in view, I see the histology of a lymph node. There is a thin fibrous capsule at the periphery, surrounded by adipose tissue (fat). The parenchyma of the node is densely populated by a monotonous sheet of small, round, dark-staining cells, which are lymphocytes. The overall architecture of the lymph node appears preserved, with a dense lymphoid population. I do not see any nests of atypical large cells, abnormal glandular structures, or other features suggestive of metastatic adenocarcinoma. My impression of this specific area is that this is a benign, reactive lymph node, negative for malignancy.
